13. Deterministic Viewpoint

Classical science uses exact relationships.

Example:

F=ma

Given:

mass,
acceleration,

force is exactly determined.

Works well in:

mechanics,
physics.
14. Limitation of Deterministic Models

Complex AI tasks are too difficult to model exactly.

Examples:

speech recognition,
language understanding,
semantic meaning.

These problems contain:

uncertainty,
ambiguity,
noise.
15. Probabilistic Viewpoint

Modern ML uses probability.

Instead of:

Y=f(X)

we treat:

X and Y

as random variables.

Probability helps model uncertainty.

16. Ignorance Modeling

Speech scientists could not fully model vocal tract physics.

Instead, they used:

repeated observations,
statistical methods.

This was called:

“Ignorance Modeling”

Modern ML follows the same philosophy:

when exact physics is too complex,
learn statistical patterns from data.
17. Important Probability Concepts
Random Experiment

Experiment with uncertain outcome.

Example:

coin toss.
Sample Space

Set of all possible outcomes.

Example:

S={H,T}
Random Variable

Maps outcomes to numbers.

Example:

X(H)=1,X(T)=0
Probability Measure

Assigns likelihood to events.

Example:

P(H)=0.5
Probability Distribution

Describes probability of values.

Examples:

Gaussian distribution,
Bernoulli distribution.
18. Large Language Models (LLMs)

LLMs work probabilistically.

Example:

Input:

“The sky is”

Model predicts probabilities for:

blue,
cloudy,
clear.

Highest probability word is selected.

